===Pronunciation===
* ''sense 1: an occurrence of disease in animals:'' {{IPA|/ɛpɪ.zəˈwɒtɪk/|/ɛpɪ.zoʊˈɒtɪk/}}
* ''sense 2: an ailment:'' {{IPA|/ɛpɪˈzuːdɪk/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{context|epidemiology}} An [[occurrence]] of a disease or [[disorder]] in a population of non-human animals at a [[frequency]] higher than that expected in a given time period.
# {{rfv-sense}} {{context|dialectal|humorous|often|_|plural}} A [[disease]] or [[ailment]].
#: ''Johnny's not doing so well today, I think he caught the '''epizootic'''.''
#* '''1986''', Geneva Bair Wilson, ''As the Anvil Rings'', page 78: 
#*: "My Laws, Minnie! She's got spots! I guess you've got the '''epizootics'''."
#* '''1977''', ''Dear Sammy: Letters from Getrude Stein and Alice Toklas'', edited by Samuel M. Steward, page 237: 
#*: Never do I have colds — but I got the '''epizootics'''(?) and sneezed my head off — twenty three times yesterday.

====Usage notes====
Used in the second sense to mean "an ailment", it is often used with the definite article ("the epizootic"), is often plural ("the epizootics"), and is sometimes written "(the) [[epizoodic]]".

====Quotations====
